\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Projection operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(You can use the Great Orthogonality Theorem [GOT] and/or the various orthogonal
ity results for the rows/columns of the character table.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The representation-theory handout gives a formula for the projection operator
 from a function onto its component that transforms as a particular representati
on.
 Using the GOT, pove the correctness of this formula: in particular, for
 any function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{i}^{(\alpha)}\psi$
\end_inset

 transforms as the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th partner function representation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 (You can use the fact, from class, that we showed that any function can
 be decomposed into a sum of partner functions of irreducible representations.
 Consider what 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{i}^{(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 does to one of thes partner functions.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that the sum of the projection operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 over all the irreducible representations 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\alpha}\hat{P}^{(\alpha)}=\sum_{\alpha,i}\hat{P}_{i}^{(\alpha)}=1$
\end_inset

 (the identity operator), by using the column-orthogonality property of
 the character table.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that the projection operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}_{i}^{(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

